    <h1>FAQs and Resources</h1>

    <details>
      <summary>Allergy</summary>
      <details>
        <summary>What are common symptoms of food allergies?</summary>
        <p>Food allergies can cause skin reactions, vomiting, breathing difficulties, and more. Symptoms usually occur within minutes to hours of eating.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is an allergy diagnosed?</summary>
        <p>Diagnosis typically involves a detailed history, physical exam, and sometimes skin prick or blood tests interpreted by a specialist.</p>
      </details>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Reflux</summary>
      <details>
        <summary>What is infant reflux?</summary>
        <p>Infant reflux is when milk comes back up from a baby’s stomach. It's common and often improves with time.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>When should I worry about reflux?</summary>
        <p>If your baby is not gaining weight, seems in pain, or vomits forcefully, speak to your doctor.</p>
      </details>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Constipation</summary>
      <details>
        <summary>How often should children poo?</summary>
        <p>It varies, but most children have a bowel movement every 1–3 days. Less frequent or painful stools may indicate constipation.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What can I do if my child is constipated?</summary>
        <p>Ensure a fibre-rich diet, plenty of fluids, and regular toilet time. For persistent problems, seek medical advice.</p>
      </details>
    </details>
